<span id="freeTextContainer3856658418786885780">I read Parades End last year and really enjoyed it, Rather expected this to be in a similar vein so was a bit taken aback on reading. Strangely enough it&apos;s not a war story but is about an American and English couple whose lives entwine over nine seasons in the early 1900&apos;s.<br/><br/>I didn&apos;t mind so much the unreliable narrator Dowell as it happens, but I did have some trouble accepting his naivety towards his wife Florence. A story of unhappy, destructive, obtuse people who are tied to each other by reli</span>
  <span id="freeText3856658418786885780" style="display:none">I read Parades End last year and really enjoyed it, Rather expected this to be in a similar vein so was a bit taken aback on reading. Strangely enough it's not a war story but is about an American and English couple whose lives entwine over nine seasons in the early 1900's.<br /><br />I didn't mind so much the unreliable narrator Dowell as it happens, but I did have some trouble accepting his naivety towards his wife Florence. A story of unhappy, destructive, obtuse people who are tied to each other by religion, appearance and the society they inhabit. I didn't like the characters on offer here but they were strangely magnetic in their own twisted perverse way.<br /><br />Well written, strangely mesmerising.</span>
